<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>751</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>zyang-000X</addr>  <route>zyang-000X.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>2</day></date>  <title>Effective quotient</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>The coequaliser of a <link href="zyang-000T.xml" type="local" title="Congruence">congruence</link> <tex>R</tex> is called the <em>quotient object</em> of <tex>R</tex>, and it is called an <em>effective quotient</em> when <tex>R</tex> is an <link href="zyang-000U.xml" type="local" title="Effective congruence">effective congruence</link>.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>752</anchor>   <addr>zyang-000Y</addr>  <route>zyang-000Y.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>2</day></date> <authors><author><link href="zyang.xml" type="local">Zhixuan Yang</link></author> </authors> <title>Effective stuff</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>1</crumb></trail> <anchor>753</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>zyang-000T</addr>  <route>zyang-000T.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>2</day></date>  <title>Congruence</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <em>congruence</em> on an object <tex>X</tex> in a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex> is an <link href="https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/congruence" type="external">internal equivalence relation</link> on <tex>X</tex>, i.e.  an internal preorder on <tex>X</tex> that is symmetric.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>2</crumb></trail> <anchor>754</anchor>  <taxon>Proposition</taxon> <addr>zyang-000U</addr>  <route>zyang-000U.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>2</day></date>  <title>Effective congruence</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Every kernel pair of a morphism <tex>f : X  \to  Y</tex> is a <link href="zyang-000T.xml" type="local" title="Congruence">congruence</link>, and such a congruence is called an <em>effective congruence</em>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>3</crumb></trail> <anchor>755</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>zyang-000X</addr>  <route>zyang-000X.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>2</day></date>  <title>Effective quotient</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>The coequaliser of a <link href="zyang-000T.xml" type="local" title="Congruence">congruence</link> <tex>R</tex> is called the <em>quotient object</em> of <tex>R</tex>, and it is called an <em>effective quotient</em> when <tex>R</tex> is an <link href="zyang-000U.xml" type="local" title="Effective congruence">effective congruence</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>4</crumb></trail> <anchor>756</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>zyang-000V</addr>  <route>zyang-000V.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>2</day></date>  <title>Effective epimorphism</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A morphism <tex>i : X  \to  Q</tex> is called an <em>effective epimorphism</em> if its kernel pair exists and it is a coequaliser of its kernel pair.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>5</crumb></trail> <anchor>757</anchor>  <taxon>Proposition</taxon> <addr>zyang-000W</addr>  <route>zyang-000W.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>2</day></date> <authors><author><link href="zyang.xml" type="local">Zhixuan Yang</link></author> </authors>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>An <link href="zyang-000X.xml" type="local" title="Effective quotient">effective quotient</link> is an <link href="zyang-000V.xml" type="local" title="Effective epimorphism">effective epimorphism</link>. That is to say, if <tex>s, t : R  \to  X</tex> is an <link href="zyang-000U.xml" type="local" title="Effective congruence">effective congruence</link> in a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>, and <tex>s, t</tex> has a coequaliser <tex>i : X  \to  Q</tex>, then <tex>s, t</tex> are also the kernel pair of <tex>i</tex>. .</p>  <block open="open"><headline><b>Proof</b>.</headline> By assumption <tex>s</tex> and <tex>t</tex> are the kernel pair of some morphism <tex>f : X  \to  Y</tex>, so <tex>f  \circ  s = f  \circ  t</tex>. Therefore there is uniquely a morphism <tex>j : Q  \to  Y</tex> such that <tex>j  \circ  i = f</tex> because <tex>i</tex> is the coequaliser of <tex>s</tex> and <tex>t</tex>.
<center><img src="resources/5bfb53f2b5481147efcc90451eb97674-web.svg"/></center>Now to show <tex>s</tex> and <tex>t</tex> are the kernel pair of <tex>i</tex>, suppose <tex>h, k : Z  \to  X</tex> is any pair of morphism such that <tex>i  \circ  h = i  \circ  k</tex>. We also have <tex display="block">f  \circ  h = j  \circ  i  \circ  h = j  \circ  i  \circ  k = f  \circ  k.</tex>Then by the assumption that <tex>s</tex> and <tex>t</tex> is the kernel pair of <tex>f</tex>, there is a unique morphism <tex>u : Z  \to  R</tex> such that <tex>s  \circ  u = h</tex> and <tex>t  \circ  u = k</tex>. Thus the square <tex>s, i, i, t</tex> is also a pullback.</block></mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>758</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>zyang-000T</addr>  <route>zyang-000T.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>2</day></date>  <title>Congruence</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <em>congruence</em> on an object <tex>X</tex> in a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex> is an <link href="https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/congruence" type="external">internal equivalence relation</link> on <tex>X</tex>, i.e.  an internal preorder on <tex>X</tex> that is symmetric.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>759</anchor>  <taxon>Proposition</taxon> <addr>zyang-000U</addr>  <route>zyang-000U.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>2</day></date>  <title>Effective congruence</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Every kernel pair of a morphism <tex>f : X  \to  Y</tex> is a <link href="zyang-000T.xml" type="local" title="Congruence">congruence</link>, and such a congruence is called an <em>effective congruence</em>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>760</anchor>  <taxon>Proposition</taxon> <addr>zyang-000W</addr>  <route>zyang-000W.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>2</day></date> <authors><author><link href="zyang.xml" type="local">Zhixuan Yang</link></author> </authors>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>An <link href="zyang-000X.xml" type="local" title="Effective quotient">effective quotient</link> is an <link href="zyang-000V.xml" type="local" title="Effective epimorphism">effective epimorphism</link>. That is to say, if <tex>s, t : R  \to  X</tex> is an <link href="zyang-000U.xml" type="local" title="Effective congruence">effective congruence</link> in a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>, and <tex>s, t</tex> has a coequaliser <tex>i : X  \to  Q</tex>, then <tex>s, t</tex> are also the kernel pair of <tex>i</tex>. .</p>  <block open="open"><headline><b>Proof</b>.</headline> By assumption <tex>s</tex> and <tex>t</tex> are the kernel pair of some morphism <tex>f : X  \to  Y</tex>, so <tex>f  \circ  s = f  \circ  t</tex>. Therefore there is uniquely a morphism <tex>j : Q  \to  Y</tex> such that <tex>j  \circ  i = f</tex> because <tex>i</tex> is the coequaliser of <tex>s</tex> and <tex>t</tex>.
<center><img src="resources/5bfb53f2b5481147efcc90451eb97674-web.svg"/></center>Now to show <tex>s</tex> and <tex>t</tex> are the kernel pair of <tex>i</tex>, suppose <tex>h, k : Z  \to  X</tex> is any pair of morphism such that <tex>i  \circ  h = i  \circ  k</tex>. We also have <tex display="block">f  \circ  h = j  \circ  i  \circ  h = j  \circ  i  \circ  k = f  \circ  k.</tex>Then by the assumption that <tex>s</tex> and <tex>t</tex> is the kernel pair of <tex>f</tex>, there is a unique morphism <tex>u : Z  \to  R</tex> such that <tex>s  \circ  u = h</tex> and <tex>t  \circ  u = k</tex>. Thus the square <tex>s, i, i, t</tex> is also a pullback.</block></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>